Southern Pilbara Rock Goanna ( Figs. 8 , 9 ,
10
)

Distribution. Known only from the Hamersley Range, a heavily dissected region of banded ironstone occupying the southern part of the Pilbara craton of Western Australia . Records span the Hamersley Range for over 300 km from east of Newman ( WAM R 125100 , WAM R 125456 ) west to Mount Rica ( WAM R 164579 ) and south to Rocklea Station ( WAM R
140734
) (Fig. 2 ).

subSection.paragraph:
Taxonomic investigations continue to reveal that species diversity in many groups of Australian lizards is higher than widely recognised. However, while there are exceptions, most of this diversity is concentrated in relatively small, non-descript species (e.g.
Horner 2007
;
Smith & Adams 2007
;
Oliver et al. 2010
). In contrast, varanids include many of the world’s largest lizards and are amongst the most high profile and recognisable components of the Australian herpetofauna. There is however evidence of significant diversity within a number of other nominal varanid species from northern Australia and further research may lead to the recognition of additional new species (
Ast 2001
; Fitch et al. 2006 ). The description of a relatively spectacular new Australian varanid, and the potential existence of additional unrecognised taxa amongst this distinctive and iconic lineage, underlines the fact that we are still far from completing the species inventory of the diverse Australian lizard fauna.
